<item>
            <title>[THRIFT-5067] Invalid Cpp generated for include guards from valid Thrift IDL when the file name has characters that are not valid in a c++ #define</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/THRIFT-5067</link>
                <project id="12310800" key="THRIFT">Thrift</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;I classify this as a bug as valid Thrift file silently generates invalid C++ code. Feel free to change the issue type if you disagree.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I use a a namespace hierarchy for my Thrift data model. When writing nested namespaces, I tend to represent to parent-child relationship of these namespaces in their the containing file names.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;So for example, I have the following relationship:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ul&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;namespace &quot;base&quot; defined in file &quot;base.thrift&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
	&lt;li&gt;name &quot;base.net&quot; defined in file &quot;base.net.thrift&quot;&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;


&lt;p&gt;Note that this convention of using dots to separate namespaces seems consistent with Thrift namespace syntax.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;The generated Cpp header for the base.net namespace does not compile: the include guard variable name uses the dot which is not valid C++ syntax.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I think the Cpp compiler should replace dots with underscores when generating the include guard.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;&#160;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
